.TH "bathfetch" 1 "@BATH_DATE@" "BATH @BATH_VERSION@" "BATH Manual"

.SH NAME
bathfetch \- retrieve profiles from a file


.SH SYNOPSIS

.nf
\fBbathfetch\fR [\fIoptions\fR] \fIhmmfile key\fR
 (retrieve HMM named \fIkey\fR)

\fBbathfetch \-f \fR[\fIoptions\fR] \fIhmmfile keyfile\fR
 (retrieve all HMMs listed in \fIkeyfile\fR)

\fBbathfetch \-\-index \fR[\fIoptions\fR] \fIhmmfile\fR
 (index \fIhmmfile\fR for rapid retrieval)
.fi


.SH DESCRIPTION

.PP
Quickly retrieves one or more profile HMMs from an
.I hmmfile
(a large profile database, for example).

.PP
For maximum speed, the
.I hmmfile
should be indexed first using
.BR "bathfetch \-\-index" .
The index is a binary file named
.IR hmmfile .ssi.
Indexing is optional; retrieval from an unindexed file is still
possible but much slower.

.PP
The default mode retrieves a single profile by name or accession,
called the
.IR key .
For example:

.nf
    \fB% bathfetch myprofiles.hmm MyProtein\fR
    \fB% bathfetch myprofiles.hmm PF00045\fR
.fi

.PP
With the
.B \-f
option, a
.I keyfile
containing a list of keys is read instead. The first
whitespace-delimited field on each non-blank, non-comment line of the
.I keyfile
is used as a key; remaining fields on the line are ignored.

.PP
When using
.B \-f
with an indexed
.IR hmmfile ,
profiles are retrieved in the order they appear in the
.IR keyfile .
Without an index, profiles are retrieved in the order they appear in
the
.IR hmmfile .

.PP
In normal use (without
.B \-\-index
or
.BR \-f ),
.I hmmfile
may be '\-' (dash), meaning reading from stdin. With
.BR \-\-index ,
stdin is not accepted. With
.BR \-f ,
either
.I hmmfile
or
.I keyfile
(but not both) may be '\-'.

.PP
By default, fetched profiles are printed to stdout in HMMER3 ASCII format.


.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.B \-h
Help; print a brief reminder of command line usage and all available
options.

.TP
.B \-f
The second command-line argument is a
.I keyfile
rather than a single
.IR key .
The first field on each line of the
.I keyfile
is used as a retrieval key (a profile name or accession). Blank lines
and comment lines (beginning with
.BR # )
are ignored.

.TP
.BI \-o " <f>"
Output the fetched profile(s) to file
.I <f>
instead of stdout.

.TP
.B \-O
Output each fetched profile to an individual file named after the
key, rather than to stdout.

.TP
.BI \-\-ct " <n>"
Use the alternate genetic code specified by NCBI translation table
number
.IR <n>
when writing the profile. The default is 1 (the standard genetic code).

.TP
.B \-\-index
Index the
.I hmmfile
for rapid future retrieval, creating the binary index file
.IR hmmfile .ssi.


.SH SEE ALSO

.BR bathsearch (1),
.BR bathbuild (1),
.BR bathconvert (1),
.BR bathstat (1)

.PP
For complete documentation, see the BATH repository:
https://github.com/TravisWheelerLab/BATH


